{"key":"processedPost-6610766","value":{"id":6610766,"first":6610766,"last":10183124,"when":1172465965,"utime":"02/26/07 06:59 AM","content":"You can see that perlite is crystalline and impervious to water, but with a large surface area to hold and evaporate it off from. <br />Vermiculite is soft and resembles a mineral sponge, able to soak up water and hold it.&nbsp; Vermiculite also has lots of passageways the mycelium can colonize while absorbing the moisture within.<br />Hopefully, these pictures will put to rest the idea of substituting one for the other.&nbsp; They're not even remotely similar.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577963-Perlite_1a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577963-thumb_Perlite_1a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577974-Vermiculite_0a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577974-thumb_Vermiculite_0a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577983-Perlite-vermiculite-dime_1a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577983-thumb_Perlite-vermiculite-dime_1a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577993-Perlite-vermiculite-dime_2.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577993-thumb_Perlite-vermiculite-dime_2.jpg\"></a> ","title":"The Difference Between Vermiculite & Perlite w/pics"}}